bug.short_desc: [Markers] Marker Resolution Dialog should use same entries as the problems view

long_desc.thetext:
The new dialog for marker resolution displays too little information in its table for similar markers: in some scenarios the resource name is just not enough, and for model-oriented markers the "Unknown" line number information is completely useless. What about extending the table to the one also used in the problems view? Together with some column filter functionality and SWT's capability to reorder columns this could be pretty convenient. As a minmum I would expect the marker text as this is the information users are most familiar with.
From the usability side: please make the table columns resizable. Also the table control does not grab vertical space if the dialog is resized.

bug.short_desc: NPE while creating SetValueCommand without domain element

long_desc.thetext:
I create SetValueCommand and pass it SetRequest instance with elementToEdit == null. I do not have elementToEdit at the moment because it will be produced by the CreateElementCommand earlier in the CompositeCommand being constructed. In other words this SetValueCommand will initialize new element right after creation. I override doExecuteWithResult() so it works fine except this NPE.

What would you like to do about SetValueCommand#canExecute in this case? Will your subclass override so that the elementToEdit is not required?

It should return true when there is no element so when it's available the command may be executed; on the other hand it's not executable if there is no element. I think that there should be a policy how the command may be used; maybe it should support deferred element update or maybe we need another command specially designed to support deferred setting of element.

Sounds good - how about I add a new subclass of SetValueCommand called DeferredSetValueCommand, then? It will be exectuable when it doesn't have an elementToEdit. Clients can subclass it to implement their own version of #getElementToEdit to find the element to edit any way they choose.
I'll still fix the SetValueCommand to prevent the NPEs when it's instantiated without an elementToEdit, but it's #canExecute method will return false if there's no elementToEdit.

Created an attachment (id=49264) Proposed fix.
Dmitri, if you have time could you look at my proposed fix to make sure it will meet your requirements before I commit? Thanks!
That's ok except canExecute() in SetValueCommand - check for null first; canExecute() in super accesses elementToEdit to get it's EClass so it'll throw NPE.

Right. Thanks for catching that!
Fixed as proposed.

bug.short_desc: 'Save As...' untitled text file sould have folder preselected

long_desc.thetext:
I20060725-0800
1. Right click on a folder in pkg explorer. 2. Select New>Untitled Text File 3. File>Save As... Is: The folder which was selected in 1 is not selected in the dialog Should: Be selected.
I see that this is an untitled text file and it has therefore no path. But anyway, it would be nice to have the folder preselected in 3, somehow.
This would be too confusing. Imagine you save an hour after step 1. and then it would use the selection you had an hour ago. Also, taking the current selection isn't a good idea in my opinion.

bug.short_desc: Proposal: Adding support to PDE Equinox Launch for additional OSGi framework implementations

long_desc.thetext:
Recently in the Apache Felix mailing list there was a discussion about the best way of launching Felix from inside Eclipse. I would like to contribute to Eclipse with a new functionality: launching different OSGi frameworks from Eclipse for plugin projects.
My Master Thesis was an Eclipse feature called eLuzien, which provides wizards, editors and launchers for developing OSGi bundles with Eclipse. The feature depends only on JDT, not PDE, as the work started last year in April, before we knew PDE was going to improve the support for developing bundles. eLuzien is hosted at http://eluzien.forge.os4os.org A basic tutorial of eLuzien can be found in the web site.
I have made some quick modifications on it to have it working on plugin nature projects (instead of the eLuzien OSGi nature) and removing all the non-launch functionality, which currently overlaps with PDE features. The current development contributes a new LaunchConfigurationType and a TabGroup where users can choose the framework implementation to run and the set of bundles to install over it. This version comes with Equinox and Felix support. You can download it from http://forge.os4os.org/frs/download.php/112/es.upm.dit.eluzien.zip
The LaunchConfiguration parameters are:the framework implementation to use, the set of bundles to launch, and a set of system properties to be interpreted by the framework and the bundles. Users can add three types of bundles to a launch: -Project bundles: Plugin-nature projects from the workspace. They are currently jarred in a temp folder and executed from there. -External bundles: Bundles in jar format stored in the filesystem. -Framework-specific bundles: Each framework implementation can supply a list of bundles which provide some basic operational functionality to the platform (i.e a textual console). They are framework dependant and are included by default in the configuration, although can be removed from the configuration manually.
Implementation details: eLuzien defines an extension point for contributing new framework implementations to the launchConfiguration. The extension declares a class which will provide the default values for a basic start. When it is time to execute a concrete configuration the delegate sends the IlaunchConfiguration object to the framework class. Each implementation returns a VMRunnerConfiguration with the necessary parameters to successfully launch the concrete config. Currently, bundles are jarred before the framework is launched..

After making some experiments I can add a Felix contribution to the extension point, although I don't think the current approach is flexible enough for generic OSGi development. The two main issues I have found until now are:
*Launching project bundles. One of the main problems with the current version comes when launching workspace bundles, as the project structure is different from an expanded bundle (binary location). Equinox solves that with an implementation specific method, the devClassLoadingHook, but this can't be translated to Felix or other framework AFAIK. One possible workaround is to generate the jars of the selected workspace bundles in a temp folder, and point the framework to that location. The main problem of this approach is that it would increase a lot the time required to test the configuration, specially compared with Equinox.
*The target platform: The current target platform model is not too well suited to generic OSGi development, as it has a strong “Eclipse flavor”. I can think of two different approaches for dealing with target platforms. -Let's assume we want to share the same target platform and choose between the frameworks. Then, the extension point needs to allow each contribution to modify the list of selected bundles appearing in BundlesTab (at least select between org.eclipse.osgi and org.apache.felix.framework or the equivalent). However, if the platform is shared by every framework, I am unsure on how well would work for the dependencies resolution part to have two system bundles exporting the packages. -Another option would be to modify the target platform when the user switches the framework, but then the user can't just switch from one framework to another, as the whole target platform would have to change (and the framework itself probably is a small part of it)
Adding “framework profiles” could be an option for addressing the limitations of the target platform approach, related to bug 154082 (Bundle Management). Plug-ins (and users) could define runtime profiles, composed of a framework implementation plus some framework-specific bundles, which can be considered part of the runtime platform, such as a text console). Some examples of profiles could be Equinox with a text console, Equinox enabled with JMX for remote management, or Felix with text console. The selected profile could appear as part of the target platform, or in a separate category. That change would probably mean that each project has to keep track of the profile it is currently targeted at, although it could be changed in any moment. The handling of runtimes in WTP can be looked at as a similar example.

I have also found a small bug with the BundlesTab: The combo for selecting frameworks registers a modifyListener, instead of a selectionListener, resulting in no notification when the target framework is changed. Changing the type of listener solves the problem. (I would attach a patch but haven't found the way to do it)

Re: comment #4, if PDE didn't treat the root of the project as a root of the bundle, but instead used a configurable bundle location (e.g. bin/ for Java-related bundles) then you could have the meta files (MANIFEST.MF etc.) hosted underneath source directories which would then be copied to appropriate locations (e.g. bin/META-INF/MAINFEST.MF) and thus all you'd need to point to a new location would be 'bin/' for everything.
This would also work for PDE too.

Well, I understand Richard's position about modifying Felix to integrate in development time with PDE. Even if Felix was changed it would not completely solve the problem, as it would happen again with each other framework implementation contributed to the extension point (Knopflerfish, Concierge). On the other hand, if the manifest was considered a source file, compiled in the bin folder, the problem would almost be solved (I suppose project resources needing to be included in the bundle should then be duplicated too in the binaries directory).
Anyway, this issue will only slow the startup time for a non-Equinox framework.
I think it is more important to improve the support for generic OSGi target platforms.

I have just uploaded a feature containing what I have been able to do with the extension point, it can be downloaded at:
http://forge.os4os.org/frs/shownotes.php?release_id=59
The plugin contributes to the extension point adding support for Felix (embedding the public 0.8.0 release). The launcher generates before setting up the VM one jar for each plugin project selected (as a workaround for the dev classpath issue). The big downside of this approach is that the user has to manually change the target platform. I played with adding the Felix framework bundle to resolve the dependencies but did not get it to work (because of the already existing org.eclipse.osgi plugin) without “destroying” the target platform and thus needing to change target whenever the user wanted to change framework. In the current version the launcher just handles the org.eclipse.osgi bundle as if it was the felix framework, resolving dependencies correctly.
The code uses several internal PDE classes (for both launch and jar generation functionality), should I open another bug for proposing changes to the visibility of some of the classes?

It would be really useful if we saw how difficult/easy it would be to support other OSGi frameworks.
Note that it may seem that Equinox is getting special treatment, but it is really not from a framework point of view.
The reason why it's easier to develop against Equinox is because the Equinox component supports -dev mode and because the PDE team has invested in an Equinox provider extension. So it took a lot of work on both the framework and the tooling to get to this state.
When it comes to other OSGi frameworks, they have two challenges: 1. Step up and come up with something equivalent to -dev. This will be framework-specific and has nothing to do with tooling. 2. Somebody has to extend the PDE extension point to support launching for that framework. This is the part that PDE is interested in making as flexible as possible for our clients.
So please open a separate bug report for your Felix client extension, and we will take a closer look at it and will discuss of whether the Eclipse SDK or PDE could benefit from providing such an extension.

bug.short_desc: EMF Transaction Infrastructure doesn't scale well for large number of small transactions in one transaction

long_desc.thetext:
With one transaction opened, create many transactions inside this transaction. Profile this scenario, and notice the intermediate memory held by the transaction infrastructure.
1. Transaction Infrastructure (ReadWriteValidatorImpl) keeps a map of transaction to its transaction tree. The entries of this map are not cleared when the child transaction is complete. Thereby the size of the map only grows when the transaction is running. 2. For every transaction, the infrastructure creates a TransactionTree. This also adds a lot of memory consumption and needs to be optimized.
By keying the txToNode Map with the root of the transaction instead of the transaction, I was able to see a lot of memory improvement.
Ignore the comment about caching using transaction root, because that doesn't work properly all the time

Updated the ReadWriteValidatorImpl to pro-actively clear references to Transactions so that they can be reclaimed earlier by GC. This includes clearing the tree node's reference to the transaction and removing the (transaction, node) mapping from the validator's map. The reduction of peak memory usage in a client application scenario generating large transactions was 11.5%.
I looked for a way to also clean up (remove) tree nodes on the fly, but this proved to be impractical: tree nodes are no longer larger than they need to be (because they no longer retain transactions), but could not be removed altogether without changing API.

I forgot to mention an important point:
A TransactionTree node is not even created any more for a transaction that is silent-unprotected and any transaction nested within it, because these do not record notifications at all.

bug.short_desc: Transaction Infrastructure keeps emf notifications cached for silent, unprotected transactions.

long_desc.thetext: EMF Transaction infrastructure keeps the cache of notifications for silent, unprotected transactions with in another transaction. This is a performance issue because it increases the memory consumption when running the transaction.
Created an attachment (id=47069) Patch for this defect

Committed a fix, different from the suggested patch. The TransactionImpl now does not allocate a list for storage when it is constructed if its options indicate that notifications will not be needed, and when it has no notifications list, the addNotification() method simply does nothing. This has a dual benefit:
- avoids the cost of an ArrayList allocation altogether - allows specialized transaction implementations to still receive notifications if they need them for some other reason
I also ensured that the list of notifications of the root-level transaction is destroyed once it commits, so that it will not persist indefinitely in CommandStacks or OperationHistorys (this applies to all transaction options).

bug.short_desc: Project references

There are multiple places related to project references: - "Project References" (any project) - "Required projects on build path" (Java, C++ project) - Web project?
Where could I find "useful documents" in the Help documentation (see bug 72841 comment 4)?

The problem is, project references have very little meaning at the generic workbench level. Other plugins may use these settings and interpret them to mean certain things, but at the platform level they don't mean much. The only place they are actually used in the base platform is in computing the build order (see Workbench User Guide > Tasks > Building resources > Changing build order). In the past they were used by JDT/PDE to mirror the build path and plugin dependencies, but they don't use project references for this any more. Other plugins in the community (such as CDT), likely still use them to reflect the build-time/runtime dependency relationship between projects.

I think the best thing to do is to update eclipse preferences instead of only update JavaCor eoptions (JDT/Core listen to preferences changes so our options will also be updated using this way...)

bug.short_desc: Mylar filter in Debug view is interfering with stepping

long_desc.thetext: Mylar filter in Debug view is interfering with stepping. So, if filter is on and I step into a method (F5) under debugging, stack trace is not updated and as result editor for new method is not opened.
A related problem is that when a breakpoint is hit the stack trace will not show. What we need to address both these problems is a 'breakpoint interaction monitor'.

It seems like current implementation of the Debug view filtering can be improved in several ways:
-- filter out all the threads except those in states "suspended" or "stepping" (take thread groups into the account and don't filter nodes for VM and processes)
-- for suspended thread only filter stack trace from bottom up to the first class that is included into the current context. Make sure that above stack frames are NOT filtered.

That sounds right to me. Anything above the stack is implicitly interesting. It reamins to be seen whether this should be implemented with predicted interest (and affect other tools/views, e.g. active test suite), or whether we should have an implicit interest rule for this view only (easier, but often this approach turns out to be a hack).

Fixed, i.e. should not be interfering with stepping anymore, but may still want to show the newly interesting (stepped into) frames. And I added code for the debug structure bridge to be able to look up and down the stack as needed, so it should not longer be too hard to do.
